ialism]]\n[[Category:Liberal socialism]]\n[[Category:Libertarian socialism]]\n[[Category:Market socialism]]\n[[Category:Marxism]]\n[[Category:Social anarchism]]\n[[Category:Social democracy]]\n[[Category:Socialism]]\n[[Category:Types of socialism]]\n", "name_user": "Davide King", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce; already wikilinked in the body", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Democratic_socialism"}
{"title_page": "Kanpy\u014d (food)", "text_new": "{{Short description|strips of dried calabash gourd used in Japanese cuisine}}\n{{For|the Japanese era|Kanpy\u014d (era)}}\n{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}}\n{{Infobox nutritional value\n| name            = Kanpyo, (dried gourd strips)\n| image           = Kampyo.JPG\n| image_size      = <!-- Defaults to 235px -->\n| image_alt       = Kanpy\u014d (raw), dried shavings of \"Lagenaria siceraria\" var. \"hispida\n| caption         = Kanpy\u014d (raw), dried shavings of ''Lagenaria siceraria'' var. ''hispida''\n| serving_size    = 100&nbsp;g\n| kJ              = 1079\n| carbs           = 65.03&nbsp;g\n| starch          = \n| sugars          = \n| lactose         = \n| fiber           = 9.8&nbsp;g\n| fat             = 0.56&nbsp;g\n| satfat          = 0.045&nbsp;g\n| transfat        = 0\n| monofat         = 0.103&nbsp;g\n| polyfat         = 0.244&nbsp;g\n| omega3fat       = \n| omega6fat       = \n| protein         = 8.58&nbsp;g\n| tryptophan      = \n| threonine       = \n| isoleucine      = \n| leucine         = \n| lysine          = \n| methionine      = \n| cystine         = \n| phenylalanine   = \n| tyrosine        = \n| valine          = \n| arginine        = \n| histidine       = \n| alanine         = \n| aspartic acid   = \n| glutamic acid   = \n| glycine         = \n| proline         = \n| serine          = \n| hydroxyproline  = \n| water           = 19.97&nbsp;g\n| cholesterol     = 0\n| alcohol         = 0\n| caffeine        = 0\n| vitA_ug         = \n| vitA_iu         = 0\n| betacarotene_ug = \n| lutein_ug       = \n| thiamin_mg      = 0\n| riboflavin_mg   = 0.044\n| niacin_mg       = 2.9\n| pantothenic_mg  = 2.553\n| vitB6_mg        = 0.532\n| folate_ug       = 61\n| vitB12_ug       = 0\n| choline_mg      = \n| vitC_mg         = 0.2\n| vitD_ug         = \n| vitD_iu         = 0\n| vitE_mg         = \n| vitK_ug         = \n| calcium_mg      = 280\n| copper_mg       = 0.433\n| iron_mg         = 5.12\n| magnesium_mg    = 125\n| manganese_mg    = 1.137\n| phosphorus_mg   = 188\n| potassium_mg    = 1582\n| selenium_ug     = 2.6\n| sodium_mg       = 15\n| zinc_mg         = 5.86\n| opt1n           = \n| opt1v           = \n| opt2n           = \n| opt2v           = \n| opt3n           = \n| opt3v           = \n| opt4n           = \n| opt4v           = \n| note            = {{Cite web | url=https://fdc.nal.usda.gov/fdc-app.html#/food-details/169241/nutrients |title = USDA Database entry for Kanpyo, (dried gourd strips)}}\n| source          = \n| source_usda     = 1\n| noRDA           = \n| float           = \n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''''Kanpy\u014d'''''|\u304b\u3093\u3074\u3087\u3046 or \u5e72\u74e2}}, sometimes [[Romanization of Japanese|romanized]] and pronounced {{transl|ja|kampy\u014d}}, are dried shavings of ''Lagenaria siceraria'' var. ''hispida'', a [[Variety (botany)|variety]] of [[calabash]] [[gourd]]. The gourd is known as {{transl|ja|yugao}} or {{transl|ja|fukube}} in Japanese.<ref name=\"Lowry\"/>  Kanpy\u014d is an ingredient in traditional [[Edo]] style [[Japanese cuisine]].  Cooked and flavored kanpy\u014d is commonly used in [[futomaki]] [[sushi]] roll.<ref name=\"Lowry\"/>\n\nKanpy\u014d was originally grown in the [[Osaka]] region.{{cn|date=July 2019}}  Now it is a [[Meibutsu|specialty product]] of [[Tochigi Prefecture]],<ref name=\"Homma\"/> where it is a [[cottage industry]].<ref name=\"Lowry\"/> The region is so tied to the food product that it hosts the \"Kanpy\u014d Highway with History and Romance\".<ref name=\"highway\"/>  The [[yuru-chara]] for [[Oyama, Tochigi]] is {{transl|ja|Kapyomaru}} ({{lang|ja|\u304b\u3074\u3087\u4e38}}, an [[anthropomorphized]] calabash.<ref name=\"highway\">{{cite web |title=\u795d\uff01\u300c\u6b74\u53f2\u3068\u30ed\u30de\u30f3\u306e\u304b\u3093\u3074\u3087\u3046\u8857\u9053\u300d\u958b\u901a |url=http://www.town.mibu.tochigi.jp/mayor/backnumber/tsushin230302.html |website=Mibu Town Tochigi |accessdate=8 July 2019 |location=321-0292\u3000\u6803\u6728\u770c\u4e0b\u90fd\u8cc0\u90e1\u58ec\u751f\u753a\u901a\u753a12\u756a22\u53f7 |language=ja |format=html |date=2 March 2011 |trans-title=Congratulation! \"History and romance Kanpy\u014d Highway\" opened}}</ref>\n\nThe gourd is harvested between late July and September. The white flesh of the gourd is cut into strips 3&nbsp;cm wide and 3&nbsp;mm thick, then either dried in the sun or dehydrated.<ref name=\"nipponika\">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Nihon Daihyakka Zensho (Nipponika) |title=\u304b\u3093\u3074\u3087\u3046 |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2012-06-07 |year=2012 |publisher=Shogakukan |location=Tokyo |language=Japanese |trans-title=Kanpy\u014d |oclc=153301537 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archivedate=2007-08-25 }}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=July 2019}}  Over 200&nbsp;tons a year of dried kanpy\u014d are produced per year.<ref name=\"Lowry\"/>  Kanpy\u014d available in the [[United States]] is sometimes chemically [[bleach]]-dried to a very white color, as opposed to the creamy color of the naturally-dried kind.<ref name=\"Homma\">{{cite book |last1=Homma |first1=Gaku |authorlink1=Gaku Homma |title=The Folk Art of Japanese Country Cooking: A Traditional Diet for Today's World |date=1991 |publisher=North Atlantic Books |isbn=9781556430985 |pages=80\u201381 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HZRDsVUZufoC&lpg=PA80&dq=Kanpyo&pg=PA80#v=onepage&q=Kanpyo&f=false |language=en |translator-last1=Busch |translator-first1=Emily |oclc=22623869}}</ref>  [[Sulfur dioxide]] is used sometimes used as a [[fumigant]] but must not be used in concentrations exceeding 5.0&nbsp;g per 1&nbsp;kg of dry matter.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u98df\u54c1\u6dfb\u52a0\u7269\u306e\u6307\u5b9a\u3001\u4f7f\u7528\u57fa\u6e96\u306e\u6539\u6b63\u7b49\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 |trans-title=About designation of food additive, revision of use standard |url=https://www.mhlw.go.jp/houdou/2004/01/h0120-4.html |website=\u539a\u751f\u52b4\u50cd\u7701 |accessdate=3 July 2019 |language=ja |format=html |date=20 January 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Dishes featuring kanpy\u014d==\n[[File:Kobumaki 001.jpg|thumb|The traditional new year dish [[kombu]]-maki tied with strips of kanpy\u014d]]\nIn addition to being the focus of many dishes, kanpy\u014d strips are frequently used as an edible [[twist tie]] in dishes such as [[fukusa-zushi]] and [[chakin-zushi]].<ref name=\"Lowry\"/>  Typically the dried strips are boiled to soften, and then boiled a second time with [[soy sauce]], [[sugar]], and other ingredients added for flavor.<ref name=\"Lowry\"/><ref name=\"Kawasumi\">{{cite book |last1=Kawasumi |first1=Ken |title=The Encyclopedia of Sushi Rolls |date=2001 |oclc=921930235 |publisher=Japan Publications Trading |isbn=9784889960761 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ybnfeu8pBMgC&lpg=PA12&dq=kampyo&pg=PA17#v=onepage&q=kampyo&f=false |accessdate=3 July 2019 |language=en |translator-last1=Driussi |translator-first1=Laura}}</ref>\n[[File:Sushi Saito IMG 1818 (23694367142).jpg|thumb|Kanpy\u014d-maki rolls]]\n*Futomaki<ref name=\"Lowry\"/><ref name=\"Kawasumi\"/>\n*Kanpy\u014d-maki, also called ''teppo maki'' (\"[[gun barrel]] maki\") as it looks like the end of a rifle<ref name=\"Lowry\">{{cite book |last1=Lowry |first1=Dave |authorlink=Dave Lowry (martial arts) |title=The Connoisseur's Guide to Sushi: Everything You Need to Know about Sushi Varieties and Accompaniments, Etiquette and Dining Tips, and More |date=2005 |oclc=962114405 |publisher=Harvard Common Press |isbn=9781558323070 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wIOcYVPYfkAC&lpg=PP38&dq=Kanpyo&pg=PP38#v=onepage&q=Kanpyo&f=false |accessdate=3 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n*Matsukasa sushi (\"pinecone sushi\"), a roll using [[squid]] filet (instead of [[nori]]) wrapped around [[sushi rice]], kanpy\u014d, [[shiitake]], [[snow pea]]s, and [[Whitefish (fisheries term)|whitefish]]<ref name=\"Lowry\"/>\n*[[Shojin dashijiru]], a [[vegan]] soup [[Stock (food)|stock]]<ref name=\"Homma\"/>\n\n[[File:Tokaido50 Minakuchi.jpg|thumb|250px|Kanpy\u014d drying in [[Minakuchi-juku]] from [[The Fifty-three Stations of the T\u014dkaid\u014d]] by [[Hiroshige]]]]\n==See also==\n* [[Oden]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kanpyo}}\n[[Category:Japanese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Dried foods]]\n[[Category:Cucurbitoideae]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|strips of dried calabash gourd used in Japanese cuisine}}\n{{For|the Japanese era|Kanpy\u014d (era)}}\n{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}}\n{{Infobox nutritional value\n| name            = Kanpyo, (dried gourd strips)\n| image           = Kampyo.JPG\n| image_size      = <!-- Defaults to 235px -->\n| image_alt       = Kanpy\u014d (raw), dried shavings of \"Lagenaria siceraria\" var. \"hispida\n| caption         = Kanpy\u014d (raw), dried shavings of ''Lagenaria siceraria'' var. ''hispida''\n| serving_size    = 100&nbsp;g\n| kJ              = 1079\n| carbs           = 65.03&nbsp;g\n| starch          = \n| sugars          = \n| lactose         = \n| fiber           = 9.8&nbsp;g\n| fat             = 0.56&nbsp;g\n| satfat          = 0.045&nbsp;g\n| transfat        = 0\n| monofat         = 0.103&nbsp;g\n| polyfat         = 0.244&nbsp;g\n| omega3fat       = \n| omega6fat       = \n| protein         = 8.58&nbsp;g\n| tryptophan      = \n| threonine       = \n| isoleucine      = \n| leucine         = \n| lysine          = \n| methionine      = \n| cystine         = \n| phenylalanine   = \n| tyrosine        = \n| valine          = \n| arginine        = \n| histidine       = \n| alanine         = \n| aspartic acid   = \n| glutamic acid   = \n| glycine         = \n| proline         = \n| serine          = \n| hydroxyproline  = \n| water           = 19.97&nbsp;g\n| cholesterol     = 0\n| alcohol         = 0\n| caffeine        = 0\n| vitA_ug         = \n| vitA_iu         = 0\n| betacarotene_ug = \n| lutein