Tochigi]] is {{transl|ja|Kapyomaru}} ({{lang|ja|\u304b\u3074\u3087\u4e38}}, an [[anthropomorphized]] calabash.<ref name=\"highway\">{{cite web |title=\u795d\uff01\u300c\u6b74\u53f2\u3068\u30ed\u30de\u30f3\u306e\u304b\u3093\u3074\u3087\u3046\u8857\u9053\u300d\u958b\u901a |url=http://www.town.mibu.tochigi.jp/mayor/backnumber/tsushin230302.html |website=Mibu Town Tochigi |accessdate=8 July 2019 |location=321-0292\u3000\u6803\u6728\u770c\u4e0b\u90fd\u8cc0\u90e1\u58ec\u751f\u753a\u901a\u753a12\u756a22\u53f7 |language=ja |format=html |date=2 March 2011 |trans-title=Congratulation! \"History and romance Kanpy\u014d Highway\" opened}}</ref>\n\nThe gourd is harvested between late July and September. The white flesh of the gourd is cut into strips 3&nbsp;cm wide and 3&nbsp;mm thick, then either dried in the sun or dehydrated.<ref name=\"nipponika\">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Nihon Daihyakka Zensho (Nipponika) |title=\u304b\u3093\u3074\u3087\u3046 |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2012-06-07 |year=2012 |publisher=Shogakukan |location=Tokyo |language=Japanese |trans-title=Kanpy\u014d |oclc=153301537 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archivedate=2007-08-25 }}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=July 2019}}  Over 200&nbsp;tons a year of dried kanpy\u014d are produced per year.<ref name=\"Lowry\"/>  Kanpy\u014d available in the [[United States]] is sometimes chemically [[bleach]]-dried to a very white color, as opposed to the creamy color of the naturally-dried kind.<ref name=\"Homma\">{{cite book |last1=Homma |first1=Gaku |authorlink1=Gaku Homma |title=The Folk Art of Japanese Country Cooking: A Traditional Diet for Today's World |date=1991 |publisher=North Atlantic Books |isbn=9781556430985 |pages=80\u201381 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HZRDsVUZufoC&lpg=PA80&dq=Kanpyo&pg=PA80#v=onepage&q=Kanpyo&f=false |language=en |translator-last1=Busch |translator-first1=Emily |oclc=22623869}}</ref>  [[Sulfu